messages.content: **14. Point 10: On Delaying the Inevitable**
I regain awareness, and examine my surroundings.
*You emerge from somewhere incomprehensible, finding yourself in a padded room. There are no exits or entrances. The walls have just began to decay, their gray surface beginning to yellow.*

“Wow.” I just kind of take in the place for a bit.

It’s not what I would’ve expected.
*Your conscience ferments in the nothing.*

What does that even mean? I grab my head.

There has to be something more. I examine one of the walls closely, then attempt to rip the padding.
*It holds up. It's held stronger than you before. You won't be allowed to hurt yourself now.*
And the floors and ceiling; they’re made of the same material?
Yeah.

“Phooey.” I mutter. This is really, seriously it? I don’t want to exert any sort of weird mental energy too much, since it’s nice not being in control for a change. But I don’t know, I doubt I have the physical strength to just bust out. I’m not some hulking bodybuilder.

I examine the seams between different surfaces; wall to ceiling, wall to floor, wall to wall. How is that handled? Is there a gap in the padding?
*There's no gap in the padding, no seams, no flaws in this chamber. It's unnaturally perfect. Escape is unlikely.*

“When you said everybody has a place like this, with somewhere else to go, I assumed you were including yourself.”

And yet for something ‘perfect’, the walls have begun decaying. I try to mess that up. Focus on the yellowing part to disrupt the padding.

*A voice emanates from nowhere. It's not the voice of the wrestler you recognize. Instead, it sounds closer to a fabricated series of sounds.* "This chamber belongs to nobody." 

*Even the yellowed walls rebuff attacks. No matter how they're perturbed, they do break, and they return to the ever-so-slightly sagging way they were before as soon as your hands come off of them.*
“I think nobody has terrible taste.” Hah.
Even if the padding was disturbed, that wouldn’t logically do anything. There’s still gotta be a more solid wall it’s attached to. But sometimes dreams have unusual rules.
"Is there any accommodation that could be made to the chamber to suit your needs?"
“…A sewing kit. Perhaps some dice. Both instances of accommodating features this room could contain.”
"We apologize, but there have been unexpected difficulties in receiving those items. However, there is a method that you can retrieve them personally."

*In a place where you just thought there was nothing, there is now a bookcase.*
"We hope this accommodation is to your satisfaction."

Just… a bunch of books? Someone else’s, but I can use them freely. A bizarre concept.

I pick the fifth book, starting from the top left, and examine it.

*Luckily for you, there are exactly five books! Without investigating the other ones, you pick up the fifth one. It's titled 'The Garden.' It is a well-aged relatively thin paperback, but it has been lovingly kept. It has four large locks on it, preventing you from opening it.*

Well, only one thing to do.

I bite one of the locks.
*It tastes... like metal. Your teeth leave small indents on the lock, but from how it feels, you think it's likely that the lock might be doing more damage to your teeth...*

Oh, I guess maybe the lock can be dealt with using one of the other books. 

I take out the fourth book. Just from a guess right now about how this works, maybe it’d have only three locks.

*The fourth book... is lock-free! *

*It's a thick book, made primarily out of cardboard. It seems to be made for children- younger children than you. On its front is emblazoned, in large letters: 'That’s The Way The News Goes'*
((so awesome))
I read TtWtNG. I used to like stories like this a lot.
Read as in the present tense. I’m not claiming to have already gone through this.

*You open it, and you are whisked away…*

*You find yourself in a large kitchen. It has more cabinets than would be in a home, but fewer than would be in a large facility. Your hand grasps a cookie jar, and you find yourself pulling out a snack. A younger child runs through the kitchen, gleaming a grin at you while running through. Strikingly, this child wears a mask covering the entire top half of their head, including their eyes.* "Come on, you're gonna miss it! All the best spots will be taken up soon!"
“Miss what?” Is this the type of story where I get to understand what’s going on, or is it just gonna be a lot of flowery imagery…

"The story! She picked this one out just for you! She'll be mad if you don't show up, doofus! You're already enough trouble for her, with your hand in the cookie jar." *He laughs, as he grabs a bag of crips from a cabinet and runs back out the door.*

Well, okay.

Am I supposed to keep the cookie? I put it back. Wait, no, is this supposed to be me reenacting some event? Maybe I need to… and it might be unsanitary to touch it and then—“Ugh. Whatever.” I just follow where he went, empty handed.

*You walk into a room, seeing dozens of childrens packed into a bizarre room that seems like a living room that might be in a regular family's house, but around four times the size. Despite this, the room is still crowded. The children all look wildly different, and each of them wear a different mask, too. Yet they all share a name, and the lack of a beginning. At the center of the room, in a large armchair, is a middle-aged woman, her mask worn, and chipped in places. She looks at you, but you can't tell what she's thinking. She points at a spot in the middle of the room, near her.*

"Come... sit."

Bizarre.
I take a seat in this occult ritual.

*The corners of the woman's mouth turn upwards, and she pulls out a book. From your close position, the title is visible: 'Kids MAKE FUN OF Boy With AUTISM, They Instantly Regret It,' written by Dhar Mann III.*

"Is everyone ready?"
I guess I’ll just intuit what autism is. I nod.

*The next 30 minutes pass vaguely as you (Scipe Discord/Ambiguous TAP reader) might imagine.*

*Like every story spoken in this room, the victimized hero has their struggle rewarded in the end. The needlessly cruel are punished, the misguided have their beliefs corrected. The structure is familiar, but the ritual feels, in some way, calming.*
*When the book closes, you look around. Every face in the crowd is silent, but their heads are all turned at you.*
“Neat.” I mean, sure, yeah. That’s nice.

"...Well, I hope everyone has learned something. I hope this has solved all of the problems we have been having recently!" *The lady in the middle stands up and leaves. As the crowd disperses, you see the kid from earlier. He's trying to get your attention, to beckon you closer to where he's sitting.*
I head over to him, I guess.
"...Hey, can you grab something for me? I'll do you a big favor if you can. I promise!"
“What do you need?”
*He points at the lady from earlier, who is now in the kitchen, occupied with preparing a meal.* "Her hairpin! I need you to get it for me! It's for something *really* important!"

This is odd. I don’t think I’d just do it it I was put into a situation like that. But again, maybe in this case… well, I’ll try. 
“Can you tell me why?” I ask, sizing up how best I’d accomplish that.
"Well, if I can get it, I'll be able to get into the *big* cookie jar. The Motherload." *He leans towards you, unnecessarily lowering his voice.* "Where she keeps the ones with marshmallows in them."
“Are there no other people with hairpins…? She’s kinda… tall.”
*He shakes his head.* "They don't let any of the kids keep any but the fragile, wooden ones. Hers is made out of metal."
Well, I’d rather not. But I’m not sure if things will change unless I do. “Do you have any ideas, or should I just wing it?”

"...I've got a replacement, right...here!" *He holds out a wooden one.* "I traded a few packs of candy for it. If you catch her while she's distracted, you can pin it up with this, then take the other one out! A perfect plan!"
I’m still hung up on the height thing. Exactly how much taller is she than me?
She's around twice your height.
Dang. If only we had a loose fitting coat, the two of us could pose as a normal sized adult.
*He follows your gaze, and nods.* "You know, if you stood on the table behind her, you could probably get a good angle..."
Is she occupied?
Yes, she's cooking.

Right. Let her cook.

Okay. I do this very silly exercise of ascending the table to perform a perfect swap. What’s the worst that could happen?
*The floor creaks as you ascend to the table, but it doesn't exceed the volume of her humming to herself. She leans back for a moment, inspecting the stew she's cooking.*

This is extremely silly!
I take this decrease in distance as my opportunity, and slide in the wooden hairpin. I then attempt to remove the metal one.

*Your assessment in the silliness of this operation is correct, but you were also correct earlier, when you surmised that you didn't have a choice. Still, as has been rehearsed, you slip the wooden hairpin and, and you remove the metal one. It's almost a perfect maneuver, and yet, at the last second, she lurches forward suddenly, and you're knocked off balance, falling forward onto the floor. She immediately turns around, and inspects you on the floor.*

"Oh my! I apologize- are you quite alright, little dearie? What were you doing!?! You could've been hurt!"

I don’t have a good lie. I barely even understand what the true answer is.
“I like climbing things.” Is what I come up with.

*She laughs, before seeing the metal pin that had fallen off, and landed on the table. She reaches back to her head, feeling for it, before finding the wooden one. She puts the pieces together, then pointing to you with the metal one.*

"Did you want this?"
“I guess.”
"Awww... sweetie, all you had to do was ask." *She gives it to you.* "I know you wouldn't do anything wrong. Please don't try and hurt yourself with any dangerous stunts anymore, okay?"
“Thank you!” This is a flagrant abuse of trust.
I return to my friend(?).

*She smiles, and spies something in the other room.* "HEY! WHAT ARE YOU DOING WITH THAT!?!?? PUT THAT DOWN!!" *She yells, leaving. The boy from earlier meets you halfway, holding a bag with him.* "That was great! Exactly how I planned."
“You could have told me that…”
*He shakes his head.* "Well, it was more like a backup." *He fetches a strange contraption out of his bag.* "...I just didn't want anyone to get in trouble." *He holds out his hand.*
I give him the hairpin.
*He slots it into the contraption, flexing it a couple times. It seems to be a kind of moving arm. It straightens out and extends to several feet, as he exclaims with joy.* "Fantastic!"
*He navigates over to a secluded corner of the room, and uses it to grab the large jar at the very top of the room. He unscrews the top, and holds it out to you.* "First pick?"
“No, you can go ahead.” I take the top.
"Suit yourself!" *He picks a cookie out, and starts to munch on it.* "...I appreciate it. That witch *hates* me."
“Why do you think that?”

"..." *He sighs.* "...It's my fault. She tells me I don't leave well enough alone. She's right. But, you know? It's boring, just doing what I'm expected to do. I want to do something people haven't done before."
“I guess so. It’s nice to have somewhere that you understand. But sometimes a home can end up as nothing but where you’re stuck.”
"Yeah..." *He shakes his head.* "All I can do is try and do what I can with it. Nothing lasts forever."

“Yeah.” I don’t actually have anything to contribute to this conversation. Was he imprisoned as a kid, or something? Perhaps some comparisons can be made.

I didn’t have such companionship, though. Not quite. It was a different set of limits.
*He aims the tub of cookies at you.* "It might make you feel better. Sometimes it's fun to break the rules."
It would be restricted for a reason, though. I know she always fretted over my diet. But fine. In the spirit of entertaining the scenario…. I accept and grab a cookie.
*You reach in, and pull out... a key! And with that, the entire scene dissolves into mist, and you return to the padded room.*
(I might have overplanned.)
((gonna call it for today yeah. that’s fine though no one is really waiting on you))
*You are in the padded room.*
Alright. Uh, the key… can I use it on one of the locks on ‘The Garden’?
*Yes. It slots in perfectly. One of the locks falls off.*
Right. But it doesn’t work for unlocking any of the others, does it.
*Correct.*
Okay. I pick one of the other books I haven’t looked at yet. Doesn’t really matter which.

*The book you pull out is a giant tome, leatherbound with gold bandings. It's titled "The Everwatch."*

*Do you open it?*
Yeah, sure.

*You open it, and you are whisked away…*

*You find yourself on a sparsely trafficked dirt road. It's a quaint little space, but just ahead of you there's a clearing with a big tree. From the clearing, you hear a small, weepy sound.*
Right. I make my way towards the direction of the noise, then.

*The clearing is a nice little area. There's a lone tree protruding from the corner. Staring up at it is a young child. She's around half your height, albeit she can't be that much younger than you.*

*This crying is not looking for attention. It is real, and it is incredibly difficult to listen to.*
“Stop it.”
"I-I'm sorry! I! It's all my fault!" *I should've mentioned earlier, but she is also wearing a mask.*
I sigh. “What’s the problem, then?”

*She looks up at you, with bleary eyes and warbly speech.* "My cat..." *She looks up at the top of the tree. Sure enough, a cat hands from the top.* "When my last cat went up the tree, he feel, and..." *She wails some more.* "They told me to never play here again, but it's- it's so pretty here! It's all my fault!"

“Yes, probably.” I look up. “If you were given fair warning… everybody has some limits they need to accept.”

“But that cat doesn’t care, does it? Just wants to climb as high as it can. There’s something to that. We obviously can’t blame the cat.”
"I... I just wanted him to see the park... it's my favorite. I... I'm so stupid!"
Well, the goal here is pretty obvious. I climb the tree.

*Your larger frame allows you to easily scale the base of the tree, and you ascend with steady, brisk pace. When you reach around halfway, the cat opens its mouth.*

"Oh, hello..." *The cat's voice is low, slow, like molasses.* "I'm afraid you're never gonna catch me."
Right. Dream. “Why not?”
"Because I'm faster and smarter." *He rears back, stretching his legs.* "And I want to be free."
“Do you think you are free? Right now?”
"In relative terms, at the very least."
“Anyone can be free relative to a less free position.” I scoff.
"Never let better be the enemy of good. Decisions in life are made on the margin."
“And you consider this free? You can’t even get down, can you? You’ve traded whatever your old cage was for an even smaller one.”
"...You don't know me. You aren't from around here. Where we are now, *anyone* can learn to surpass their boundaries. Even me. Even *you.* Here, I am free. Here, I have control."
“I don’t think so.” I try to grab the cat. Maybe it really is that simple.

*The cat jumps from the top of the tree. It looks like it's trying to get out of your grasp, at all costs, but then...*

*Feathery wings sprout from the sides of its body. It floats down, and begins to hover a foot and a half away from you, mocking you.*

"I'm as free as a... well, Looks like I'm the bird, and *you're* the one in the cage." *He gloats.*
This is stupid.
“Cats can’t fly.”
"Maybe you're the stupid one for believing that all this time." *His grin grows wider. He levitates in a leaning back position, front paws behind his head, looking down at you.*
“You can’t even go anywhere! You’re not even an actual cat!”
"You're not an actual girl! Ha! How about that! If you were who you're *supposed* to be, you wouldn't be dangling off that tree like a ninny!"

“What does that even mean?” This guy… big man, or whatever, he’s a boy. Or would’ve been in his childhood. So is this denigration of his masculinity, since the actual cat is speaking to… wait, no! There’s no way this literally happened.

“What compels you towards this freedom? Is freedom worth anything intrinsically?”

"Free to answer your questions, free to not. You tried to grab me on the tree. I was just trying to have a nice conversation."

*He lowers to your height and blows a raspberry at you.*
“Has the girl down there wronged you?”
"Of course not! Unless you count being named 'Toast' a wronging of substance..."
Now that I’ve gotten the cat to lower itself to my level, I try to get it talking long enough to be distracted enough that I can grab it. “That’s unusual. Why toast?”

"You see I imagine it has something to do with perceived aesthetic similarity. It's quite a unique effect actually, toast (the foodstuff) is perceived as warm, fluffy, and inviting. I imagine by naming me for this object, she intended to suggest those vague characteristics about me (or even make an observation) by labeling me with the more detached object. It gives my persona the connotative value attributable to the object without being as on-the-nose as simply labeling me with the attribute. It's comical- it seems these children have thoughtlessly invoked a storytelling device that some seasoned artists haven't even mastered!"
I tackle the flying cat.

*You leap out! The distance between you and the cat closes, closes, but then, quickly, he curls up, allowing himself to freefall, and he narrowly dodges out of your path. Oh no, you were up really high, and now you are accelerating towards the Earth that is directly in front of you...*

*But then you feel something on your sides, and suddenly, wings burst out of your own sides as well! You instinctually pull up, and begin flying, seeing the cat now beginning to flee.*

"Wonderful! Now the chase begins!"
I fly after him for a bit to check if he’s just clearly faster than me.
*Nope. You seem to be a bit faster, but he has a little lead. As you chase him, the world starts to twist around you. The flat landscapes begin to roll, and tumble around you.*
Whoa.
Uh, can I like… what if I try to corner him using the terrain?

*Gravity seems to change at random around you. Still, you weave him into a corner. His myopic brain doesn't navigate him as well as it does you. He doesn't realize he's being closed in.*

"Why are you chasing me anyway? I can just run away again later. You can fix me but you *can't* make sure anything ever stays fixed."
“Why not? Seems you’re making assumptions about what I’m free to accomplish.”
"Everything stays, Eulogia. But it still changes. Rules of life."
*The name easily comes off the creature's lips.*
“And the rules? Do they change?”
"Not unless anybody changes them."
*You continue chasing him into a corner.*
“Maybe I will.”
*The world streams above and below, and you see the opportunity to finally corner the cat. Do you?*
I do.
*You corner it on the ground, and it wails in mock agony.* "Augh! Gadzooks. What a tragedy that has befallen me..."
“Mhm. Sure.”

"If you have no other revelry..." *He extends his paw, and flicks his fingers. The wings vanish, the city falls back into rank-and-file, but it's all sideways. You begin to plummet through the town...*
Oh.
I mean, if there’s not a floor I’m gonna fall to, this is just an inconvenience.
*Suddenly, a green haze comes into your field of view. It approaches...*

*You pass by a few windows of people. Voices call out.*

"Yeah, you got it!"
"You're the best!"
"Wooo-hooo!!!!"
This probably represents something.
I give a thumbs up to the people, however readable it may be with our respective orientations.

*You hit the green haze, still carrying the cat.*

*And then you're in the park again, crawling out of a bush near the tree's base. Everything vaguely hurts, but you got Toast. Seems like it always lands Eulogia-side down though.*

*The girl cries out.*

"Are you okay!?!?!?"
“Yeah!” Probably, I think.
"And you got Toast!!!! Oh my god! Thank you!" *She holds out her arms.*
I hand her the cat named bread.

*The cat tries to escape in her arms for 2.1243712 seconds then immediately nuzzles up to her, purring. She wastes no time petting the cat before setting it down, and it goes to sleep.* "Thank you so much! You're the best ever!" *She goes to a nearby patch of flowers to pick a flower.*
“Yeah, good, okay.” Uh, I did it? Am I supposed to … talk to her?
*She picks a dandelion, and walks back to you, holding it out to you.* "Take this! You're my hero, Mr. Man!"

Unusual. So she doesn’t see me as Eulogia. Is that to indicate that this really happened? 

I accept the flower.
*You take it, and it turns into a key in your hands. And with that, the entire scene dissolves into mist, and you return to the padded room.*
((~~dissolves into WHAT~~))
Okay. Same thing again, one more lock down on the final book.
*Indeed! You're halfway there! And you have a feeling the final book will be pretty short, too.*
I guess I do? I dunno. I pick up the remaining book that is further to the left.

*The next book is 'You* ***MUST*** *Make a decision: Lamp Deathmatch'.*
*It's a comic book. And not an extremely classy one.*
A demanding read. I open it.

*You open it, and you are whisked away…*

*You are in a plane of darkness. It's lit with spotlights. In the distance is... well, it's hard to see. There's a spotlight in a couple dozen feet or so.*
I walk to that one, then.

*You're in a guardhouse station. A guard nods at you. His mask is angular, rigid.*

"Thank you. You've been a good help today, regardless if- regardless what-" *He sighs.* "Thank you for detaining this man. We will still be in contact with you."

"Oh. And when the time comes, go with left."
“Who is left.”

"Hahaha. Left, of course!"

*Suddenly, a raving thing lashes out from behind the cell bars barely visible.*

"NO! Too the riiight.... you want to go with the riiiiight... of course!"
“So much for the left.” I mutter. Where even am I hang on
*You're still in the first spotlight, but a veil of a police station has been cast over it. You can still faintly see the other spotlights, and even the thing in the distance.*
Ok I go. Uh. I head to the spotlight closest to the right from where I’m currently facing

*They're all in a line (leading up to the thing in the distance, but you progress to the next one).*

*You're at a schoolyard. You're standing in front of around one thousand children. An older gentleman in a wheelchair speaks to you, but he talks loud enough for the crowd to hear.*

"And I'd like to expend a special thank you for amping up our school for the incoming test season. It's been very helpful. But I, and I think a lot of the kids, have a single question for you."
I await him explaining what the question is.
"What are you thinking. Left or Right?"

I feel like I’m missing most of the relevance here. This guy is weird.
“Right.” I state with feigned confidence.

"Ah yes, I'm a right guy myself."

*The crowd erupts in cheers and boos, of about equal measure. Several 'I told you so' and 'I'm so betrayed!' faces are glared at you by the audience, and the volume rises considerably. The old man tries to quiet the children, but it seems no end is in sight.*

Is this a politics thing? I know like… different parts of the kingdom. Or something.

I move on.

*As you approach, the distant location is more clear. It's an... arena, of some kind.*

*You are in a bar, where you are sipping something that tastes gross... but healthy. Someone from the corner of the room whistles loudly, and raises a glass to you.*
Thanks, corner guy, who I look at. Must be nice to be so popular.
"Haha, left or right, haha!?!? You decide! Only you, Big Man. Hahahahaha!" *Murmurs begin to escalate around you. People discussing around them. Left or Right? It is a big dilemma.*
Oh, it’s like. The point is that it doesn’t mean anything. Because he doesn’t care?
Sure. I’m going to move on.

*You approach the final destination. It's a combat arena.*

"Welcome one and all to the fourth ever Lamp Deathmatch!"

*The scene before you makes the literality of the name obvious. The two people in the arena are prepared to fight, and the lamps in the arena are prepared to be used as weapons. You can only imagine what this will do to the contestants, or the people in the crowd. Aren't those lamps filled with dangerous gases? Aren't microscopic glass particles bad for the breathing system?*

"You know the rules, no holds-barred, two rounds each, and they're rearing to go!"

*Two gigantic people stand in the ring, sizing each other up.*
I… guess I would be a little concerned about that? I’m sort of taking this at face value. I didn’t get very far objecting to the winged cat.
But yeah I guess it would be dangerous to fight with lamps
Um
I see if anything happens
I don’t know if I’m supposed to do something here

(Yeah this one is kinda the most linear things just happen to you. Comic books lol. Also joke of decisions mattering.)
*They begin fighting. The person on one side opens his mouth.*
"Diz-dam Whing whang Ting Tang. Eat sleep Wake eat Walla walla Bing Bang."
*The person on the other side retorts.*
"Oh lad. So sad. Big bad. Eat hat Ice hat Poliwag Flip Flap."
*Lamps get broken. Glass shatters. Blood is drawn. This is so silly.*
*A bell rings out.*
"AND GIVE IT UP FOR ROUND 1!!!!"
*The audience is losing their shit.*
Okay cool. Uh. Great. “Yeah.”

*They continue.*
"Ice cream, brain freeze, big sneeze ! Joke fees! Joe Please!"
*The acrobatics on display are too ludicrous to be described in words.*
"Koala Koala Koala Koala Koala Koala Koala!"
*They rush at each other, blasting each other with a final dusting of glass and blood, as the second bell tolls.*

"Okay! We've got our two rounds of combat over, and the match will come down to decision! And the judges... are completely tied up, which means it all comes down to our guest judge!" *The arena's spotlights all center on you.*

"Who do you give it to? Lux Left or Rickert Right?"
Which one said Koala? I think it was probably the right guy. “Right.”

*One of them pops up really high. The entire arena is a cacophany of noise, with people on the full emotional spectrum.*

"WELL THERE YOU HAVE IT THERE! Rickert Right takes it, and-" *The speaker dissolves into static noise.*

"Psst!" *From behind, someone calls you over. "You're not from around here."
I look at the someone. How do they mean that…

"Hey. You see, technically, I was here for this, so I get to live here now. It's pretty sweet. My name's That's The Point.

You have it wrong, by the way."
“Have… what wrong?”

"It's not that he doesn't care. He cares a *lot.* But this scene... it's played out thousands of times. They all go the same way."

*He holds a key out to you, ready to take whenever you want it.*

"*That's* the point."

“Ohhh. I see. It’s like that, then.”
I grab the key.
*With that, the entire scene dissolves into mist, and you return to the padded room.*
“I still might not get it.”
((good place to stop for today))
(Yeah, next session we'll probably clear it. I think the next book is the longest but it's also my favorite.)
The padded room, still?
Yup
I take the one unexamined book.

*This book has no title, or at least, you can't make it out anymore- the front is badly damaged.*

*This book gives you a dark feeling when you pick it up. It feels fragile, in your hands, like it could fall apart at any moment. It cannot. It is made of something stronger. A flood could destroy all the other books, and yet this one would remain. Why?*

“They say that any hardship you survive only helps to make you stronger and greater. …I think that’s just a bunch of nonsense, though. If you can’t control something, you control what you think it is.”

But still, it’s no more unreasonable than a flying cat.

It won’t fall apart because it’s not supposed to. It isn’t allowed to. It would violate the rules of the game. That’s my guess. Maybe being granted that staying power is the real damage. 

…What does that even mean?

“Well, it’s just a book.” I open it.

*You open it, and you are whisked away…*

*You find yourself in a room with a lot of discarded objects. It seems like you're in some kind of warehouse or something, laying about in a heap of half-put together devices, antique clothes, and dismantled furniture. *

*People are scrambling about everywhere. However, while they all have masks on, some have paper tapestries comically covering their masks as they amble about. Everybody is rushing to a different location, like insects in a nest. Above the din, a voice emanates.*

"Where's my guy? Where the fuck is he? He should be here by now."

Am I the guy? 

I try to get my bearings and get onto my feet, while looking for the source of the voice.
*It seems as if there's someone in command of this chaos, a slovenly balding man sitting on a beaten-up chair in the middle of this cacophany, cursing at nobody in particular. He is the source.*
I wander over to the guy. “What’s all this, then?”

*He takes one look at you. His countenance breaks for a second.*

"Okay hold up who brought their kid in here? She's not on the call sheet- c- can I get the stage manager back here? Inkelmann! Over here!" *He calls, and a tiny man runs over, sweating profusely.*

"Yes, what is it sir?"

"There's no kid on the backstage sheet, right?"

*Inkelmann browses quickly through papers on his clipboard, pausing at one.* "Errr.... no, sir."

*The man in the chair shakes his head at you.* "And where is my Annice!? I swear to god, I give people here one ounce of freedom, and..." *He shakes his head, as the small man looks at you.*

I contacted a different sort of coworker. Someone I don't tend to speak to."

She makes an exasperated noise. "You're still on that level of understanding, I guess. I still kind of have to avoid spoiling things related to that, infuriatingly. None of them agreed with my memory of events. Nobody could understand anything I thought was odd. Most importantly, just..."

I stepped back somewhat. "What is this... claw?"

Also Klaud is kind of dead, but that part’s complicated.” She presses some buttons on a remote. “You ever have to have surgery for one reason or another, Endo?”
"Yes. Are you implying something?"

“Not really. Awkwardly making conversation. I needed to get a pacemaker implanted. Regulate my heart so I didn’t, you know, fucking die. Just another weakness of the body. And they gotta put you under for that shit; like, trick your body into getting what it needs to survive. Ridiculous.”
"But why did your heart need to be regulated? What was the specific malfunction at play?"
“Cardiac arrhythmia. I’m not a doctor, but I’d definitely be dead by now without that sort of technology.”
*She nods.* "Modern medicine is a marvel, and an undeniable showing of the power of the truth."

"Even with all of its weaknesses, however, the human body itself is remarkably resilient. The fact that the heart can typically continue to beat perfectly, ad-nauseum, for dozens of years, is an impressive feat of engineering."

"By 'engineering', I refer to the natural process of evolution, of course. From a human perspective, the body is a technological marvel, but thousands of other animals all have similar biological processes allowing them to survive."
“That’s the thing. It’s an impressive accomplishment over a time scale of millennia. Things are accelerating.” Ganna wipes her brow.
"Exponential growth. And one can only hope that it continues to accelerate."

“Hope… isn’t enough for me.” She presses a button, and the ceiling claw-looking-thing rotates rapidly.

“It’s an active effort.” She stares ahead at nothing in particular. Her eyes betray nothing. No emotion or sentiment. Only impatience.
*She steps back further.* "So you wish to... advance the state of medicine?"

“I wouldn’t really say—“

Ganna “Soul” Oppineta is struck, electrocuted by the mechanism on the ceiling. Her body collapses onto the floor as the mechanism decelerates to a halt.
*She runs up to "Soul".* "*What?* Are you okay?"
*She feels for a pulse.*

No pulse.

The room hums to life, most of the deactivated screens turning on.

Her voice is heard again. “It’s fine. I’m fine. Just as planned.”
"Is this a prank?"
“Not really. But I suppose it feels like you’re being screwed with. A necessary evil.”
"I do not need to be here."
“You do, though. Someone did, at least. Klaud’s not around, and I definitely wouldn’t have been able to convince any of the others to go with me.”
"Now what?"
“That’s all from me. You’ve got only minutes left in this chapter, so I’ll hear out any final questions.”
"What are you talking about? Why would I need to 'go with you' to... do nothing?"
“You needed to observe. It needed to be seen.”
"No it didn't."
“It did. It means everything. You know what I call being obsessed with the truth when you don’t know any of it?”
"Depression?"

“A parasocial relationship.”

End chapter.

messages.content: ((this just fucking happens in tap damn))

All of a sudden, Furn suddenly shows up, breaking the floor and climbing through like some sort of unbound-by-gravity Kool-Aid man. ((I am ending the session on this stupid fucking cliffhanger because DND combat drained all of my power))

Furn stares at Nerissa.
Nerissa stares at Furn. 
Furn stares at Gratia.
Nerissa stares at Furn.
Furn stares at you.
Nerissa stares at Furn.
Furn stares at Nerissa.

“Do I… know you?” He mutters in her general direction.

“No. Certainly not.” Nerissa scoffs.

“Okay.”

It is somehow really awkward and quiet now, and Gratia is still  dead looking, and the ship is still collapsing.
((We do not have to go I know in a different server you seemed caught off guard that this was happening))

"Gweh... Gweheh... GWEHAHAHAH! Yes! My metallic minion, finish off this fool not worthy of witnessing the true power of Voreverl Leocot! Do you see? Do you understand the machinations at play here!? I wasn't just focused on fighting you, I was summoning a trump card! There are cogs within cogs of my Machiavellian machine of evil!"

“So this thing also intends to interfere?” Nerissa.

“I suppose. Is this, uh, the guy?” He looks at Voreverl.

Voreverl kind of dejectedly kicks at the ground "She's *a* guy, I guess. She's no hero! Just some random other unimportant villain that intends to stop my reign of terror! But yes, I do believe Jill Bobs sent us here to kill her. So, get on it."

“I am a hero. Obviously. Why would a self-proclaimed villain be honest?”

Furn smolders. “Okay, but that would just mean I have even more reason to fight you.”

“I don’t care about that. I only care about principles. You should not operate under delusions in your goals.” Nerissa sighs. “I believe your comrade is under a fundamental misunderstanding caused by ineptitude.”

"Oh, yeah? Well, your flying fortress is undergoing a fundamental failure due to *your* ineptitude! You don't get to be a pathetic delusional shut-in whose only friends are robots and then criticize *me*! Actually, no one gets to criticize Voreverl Leocot!"

“I suppose I should have safeguarded against teleportation. That illustrates nothing, though. Heroes aren’t infallible. Not from the start, anyway. No one would read stories if they were.”

“I’ve realized I don’t actually care about whatever this is.” Furn attempts to rush Nerissa with his incredibly slow self. This fails, and she knocks him back a few feet. Her heart just doesn’t seem to be in this one.

Voreverl throws up her arms in frustration "*Really*? That's the best you've got!? You're giant! You're made of metal! How are you being beaten by someone other than Voreverl Leocot!? She's not even, like, metal-bending you or whatever! Just crush her!"

“I’m a little woozy.” Furn is slow to get up.

“It’s horribly inefficient, you know. I could probably power this entire vehicle for days with the energy wasted to take a step were the means to conversion only available for me.” Nerissa looks at Voreverl while saying this, chiding her.

"...What? I mean, uh, gweheheh! Yes! Inefficient energy is yet another one of Voreverl Leocot's evil schemes! Solar? Wind? Hydro? Foolish! I'll leave the environment in a state of ruin! And, and then charge for breathable air! Be terrified by my blatant disregard for efficient energy use!"

“No, it’s just stupid. You are wasting your own resources. You’re stupid.”

“Air pollution actually got solved a few years back. You can just purify it with minerals, or something. Innovative stuff.” Furn launches an orb of flame at Nerissa.

"Oh come on! Polluting the air is... it's every child's dream! It's *the* villain plan! Destroy the world, but leave just enough left to support life. As long as humanity went on, every breath they take would remind them of me! Voreverl Leocot!" Voreverl droops her shoulders "Whatever. I've got thousands of plans. No used crying over pasteurized milk."

Nerissa’s dress is singed, pissing her off. “Like your amazing plan to take this vessel down? The one you stand to benefit from in no way? Which would kill you anyway were it to succeed? That level of competence? Must have taken quite some time to think of that many.” She kicks Furn, which doesn’t actually do anything to him.

"Gweheheheh... You really don't know anything do you? Of course I'm not that shortsighted! I'm an evil genius! I happen to be traveling with a woman capable of using teleportation magic. We'll simply kill you and leave. As for what I gain... I gain the death of this symbol! The greatest terrorist attack in decades! A crumbling, crashing, flaming wreckage falling the ground! What better to represent the start of the age of Voreverl Leocot!?"
“What woman? *That* one?” She points to Gratia, a diversion of attention that allows Furn to wallop her in the face.

"Of course not. Keep your jokers face down, as I say. Gratia here is nothing but a meat shield, and maybe comedy relief. Every evil empire needs a... court jester..." Voreverl struggles a bit to get those last words out.
“I have no need for jokers!” She sets up a defensive barrier. “You’re quite like the fool tarot yourself, Leocot! Your outer side conceals your lack of value!”
((My entire life has led to this message.))

"Lack of value, you say? Gweheheh, you know, I compared the worth of your attacks to that of a penny earlier, but perhaps that was an insult to pennies. Abraham Lincoln may have taken on the role of a villain, but after accidentally ending slavery, he failed at even that. You, though... You couldn't even bumble your way into a heroic deed! You've enslaved not only human souls, but a whole crew of robots to do your bidding! You're a tyrant, just like me!"

“This is absurd. Was the Emperor of days gone by a tyrant simply for commissioning the construction of monuments without providing the workers compensation? Of course not. And I am purely more noble; I toil over the well being of these pathetic things, and I extol the glory of my collaborators.” She sighs. “Ideally, I *would* be able to receive direct confirmation of their consent, but such a path is unfortunately not viable.”
Furn is punching the barrier a bunch like that one Metal Gear Rising gif 

“And the mechanical ones! As if an object could present some ethical question. The useless cretin Fema who fell down there doesn’t have a *soul*. She’s a girl without a heart who I still have spent hours and hours on the upkeep of, just like all of my crew. You’re the only one I’ve seen screwed up enough to bind actual life to a facsimile of a person!” She grimaces at Furn.

"I did wha-" Voreverl cuts herself off, and a smug grin fills her face "Ah! Of course! My disgusting creature! My Frankenstein! My abomination against the sanctity of life itself! As an inferior villain, you must be disappointed you didn't think of it first! But of course you didn't! For I, Voreverl Leocot, am the only villain brilliant enough to create a being as revolting as this!"

“Don’t push it.” Furn grunts.

“I mean, it’s disgusting. Just an abomination. I feel an overwhelming urge to know more… to avoid such horrors! For instance, how was it done?! Did you concoct it artificially, or transplant the soul of something alive? Why did you see fit to add more than one? How could anyone ever hope to stabilize a—”

“Wait, hold on.” Furn stops punching the barrier. He didn’t seem to be making much progress. “What are you talking about? I’m only one guy. I might not know who that was before being me, but it’s still just the one.”

“Your ignorance astounds. Though I suppose being able to ‘know’ at all is a miracle for you. There’s about three. All bunched up. I can see with my eyes because they are special and better than everyone else ever.”

Furn is silent, and Nerissa busy storing energy for some reason or another. “Wait, is *that* what happened? Why I suddenly stopped being able to…”

He suddenly turns to Voreverl. “Hey, wait a minute! You left me for dead! What the hell is wrong with you?”

"Well, that's... Gweh... You see..." Her eyes start darting around, before she clenches her fists and takes a breath "...You simply outlived your usefulness as a minion. Knocked around and left behind by a simple engine explosion? Gwehah! If that did you in, then you were never strong enough to assist me in the slightest! And what better demonstration of evil is there than kicking a weak character while they're down!?"

“Oh, sure. Well, I wouldn’t want to get in your way. Go ahead! Defeat her! I’ve shown my pitiful limits already.” Furn sits down.

“Do you two need… a moment? I don’t understand what this is.” Nerissa is still within her ABSOLUTELY SAFE ZONE.

"Voreverl Leocot does not need filler arcs! If Furn's feelings are hurt, then his lack of skin simply wasn't thick enough! No, actually, it was exactly thick enough! Because it showed off how evil I am! Gweheheh!" Voreverl looks back and forth between Furn and Nerissa a few times before clicking her tongue "Of course, I could show off my power as a villain here, but I already did that plenty... before you got here! Now, I'll... Yes, I'll *intimidate* you into fighting for me! You won't dare to slack off ever again!"

“No. No, I think this is it. We had a good thing going, Voreverl. We had Wress. We had Katrielle. We had the potential for asynchronous collaboration. We had some good progress on all these mysteries. But you just had to go and screw it all up, one after the other, huh? You, and your pride, and your ego. Well, I can take pride myself in being the end of the line. The final betrayal of the legendary Voreverl Leocot. Nice ring to it.”

“Ach! DeodanaFAEX!” Nerissa glances to the side, then lets her guard down and sprints back to the smaller control station.

"Th-that''s..." Voreverl glances around nervously "But... no! I'm... I'm not legendary yet, I haven't even started... No, of course I have, I'm the greatest villain to ever live! I... Can I die here... No... I haven't even..." Voreverl grabs her head and her stance starts to waver "Eric! Eric! I need to find Eric again! He knows what to do! He... I'll take back my life! I have to! Get out of my way! Everyone get out of my way!"

Furn tackles Voreverl… and then everything goes black.

End chapter.
